description.text:
This version is for 1/8" thick acrylic, rather than 1/4", and half the height. A single 12"x12" stock will get you two complete nave sections, i.e. eight times the Gothy goodness of the original.
Isn't multiplication fun?

Because I didn't know what the kerf was, the tab/slot thickness was a little loose. A hot glue gun fixed that in a jiffy!
Nota Bene: The ladder-like pattern in the upper right corner is a kerf measurement pattern. You can remove it if you know, or don't want to know, your kerf.
The idea is to make several close cuts in the material, then stack the pieces and measure the material lost to the laser.

This is it! This is the legendary Bathynomous giganteus. The giant, deep-sea isopod that prowls the deep Gulf of Mexico, ravaging whalefalls, scavenging scraps. The living embodiment of large and in charge.

Roly poly. Pill bug. Wood louse. Whatever you call the adorable pill-sized isopods that crawl out from soggy logs, this is their cat-sized big sister.

For years, I've been fascinated by giant isopods. Though many specimens have passed through my lab, they were never in good enough condition to make a solid 3D scan. Now, at last, fortune and opportunity have coalescent around this one perfect isopod, to be immortalized and duplicated.

Read a bit about the biology and ecology of the giant deep-sea isopod in our epic monograph: Sizing ocean giants: patterns of intraspecific size variation in marine megafauna.

Observe the behavior of these mighty and enigmatic arthropods in these two videos:

Giant deep-sea isopod digging a burrow and Giant deep-sea isopod swims away

Help me continue to make true-to-life 3D models of marine organisms, as well as my other ocean science initiatives by supporting me on Patreon. Even a dollar or two a month goes a long way towards the continued development of my ocean projects.

In the deep Gulf of Mexico, there dwelt a giant isopod. In fact, there dwelt many thousands of giant isopods. One day, or, perhaps many days over the course of a field season, a great trawl descended upon them, and carried them to the surface. After many months of study, they were resigned to the deep freezer, where they waited for years, maybe decades, for the next deep-sea biologist to pull them out and study them.

But retirement happened first, and they languished until, at last, they were passed on to a colleague and friend, who recognized their value. From that great pile of isopods we found the perfect one.

This isopod was scanned with a smartphone, using 123D Catch, edited in Meshmixer and 3D Builder, and printed on a Printrbot with Repetier.

description.text:
If you don't use the flashlight in your e46 BMW glovebox, here is a nice USB port adaptor that will plug right into the dash and give you two switched ports!

I removed the center of the flashlight receptacle with a screwdriver and removed the pins, which are reused in the new adapter.

Print both pieces, then wire two of these buck converters with 18AWG wire.

https://www.amazon.com/dp/B00CGRMGZM/ref=sr_ph_1?ie=UTF8&qid=1475731913&sr=sr-1&keywords=buck+converter

There is not a lot of space, so you need to be delicate. Pin closest the the edge is negative. Solder the lead wires to the pins before inserting from the bottom - be careful not to insert too far.

Push the assembled converter into the receptacle, push the female connector housing onto the back, plug in the wire from the car and re-insert into the glovebox. Two 5v/3A ports!

description.text:
This little paper cup holder is an exercise in Clifford Smyth's method of cutting a design into parts that can be printed on their sides - for strength - and quickly fastened together with Super Glue. More details are in my blog about it.

IMPORTANT NOTE: Do not use this holder daily unless you create a Food-Safe print. Even non-toxic prints are very porous, allowing bacteria and fungus to grow. I believe Shapeways can print Food-Safe prints.

This part is designed to use no support at all. The square tube, when cut in half diagonally, produces walls at 45 degrees. Most 3D printers can print a wall at 45 degrees with no support.
After printing, glue the two halves together with a small amount of Super Glue. Follow all the precautions on the Super Glue bottle.

As you can see in the screen shots, I first designed the part, then created a block that I subtracted from the design to create one of the two halves to be printed. I repeated the process to create the other half.

I printed the parts on their sides, for maximum strength and zero support structures.

description.text:
Not the last one, the latest one.

This is a new version of http://www.thingiverse.com/thing:1613943. I changed the desigen a bit and I split the "key holder_1" in two parts, so I dont need any support material to print the parts.
The parts "key holder 1A" and "key holder 1B" are glued together and screwed to "key holder 2" via three round spacers. I have used these round spacers (https://www.hstronic-gmbh.de/Abstandsrollen-Messing-vernickelt-Innendurchmesser-26-mm-fuer-Gewinde-M25) and cut a M3 thread inside.

There are two versions of the key organizer.

The first version is for up to nine keys and the second version for up to five keys.

Parts for version one :
3x round spacers L=12mm, 1x locking disc_9 keys.stl, 1x key holder_1A.stl, 1x key holder_1B.stl , 1 x key holder_2.stl , 1x keychain.stl and spacer.stl to prevent the rattle if less than nine keys are installed (For example 2 spacer if you only have seven keys).
6x M3x6 countersink screw (DIN 965) , 1x M3 washer.

Parts for version two :
3x round spacers L=7mm, 1x locking disc_5 keys.stl, 1x key holder_1A.stl, 1x key holder_1B.stl , 1 x key holder_2.stl , 1x keychain.stl and spacer.stl to prevent the rattle if less than nine keys are installed (For example 2 spacer if you only have three keys).
6x M3x6 countersink screw (DIN 965) , 1x M3 washer.

Nintendo NES controller inspired hand held game console with 8x8 LED matrix display!

Update April 2017

  • New firmware integrates Doodle Jump with the rest of the games, also adds 'Flashy Bird' and sound effects in the main file.
  • I had a batch PCBs made professionally. They are available for US$10 + postage, send me a message if interested. I will also consider putting together a kit of all non-printed parts.

**

This console is based on an Arduino Nano and a 1.2" 8x8 LED matrix display with a HT16K33 driver. Both of these are available cheaply from eBay, Total build cost should be under $20 (assuming you can make your own PCB).

The 'Nantendo' firmware has Pong, Space Invaders, Snake, Breakout and a Car driving game as well as a slightly weird game called 'Tedshow'.

The firmware is adapted from here:
http://letsmakerobots.com/node/44115
The main differences are that this design uses a different display driver and uses buttons rather than a potentiometer for left-right control.

Alternatively, there is an adapted version of 'DoodleJump' based on this:
https://github.com/brnunes/Arduino-Doodle-Jump

There is another adaptation of all the games with sound and including Doodle Jump here, however it is not quite as stable:
https://hackaday.io/project/12310-diy-led-8x8-matrix-game-console-64bit

I am planning to merge the sound effects and other games back in in the future.

Instructions:

  • Print parts according to the Bill of Materials
  • Print the label onto adhesive material and cut it out with a scalpel
  • Make the PCB from the Eagle files
  • Assemble the PCB
  • Copy the Arduino libraries from the libraries folder in 'Arduino_Nantendo.zip' into your own Arduino libraries folder (usually, Documents / Arduino / libraries)
  • Load the firmware using the Arduino host software and a USB mini cable
  • Assemble the housing
  • Get playing!

PCB assembly notes:

  • If your 8x8 display comes with right angle header connectors, remove them by cutting the pins, pulling off the plastic part then carefully desoldering each pin - see photo
  • Use a 4-way straight header to connect the display to the PCB.
  • Optinally, use 1 or 2 printed spacers and M2 screws to steady the top of the display. I just screwed into the PCB then cut the screws flush at the back since they are behind the battery holder. Alternatively you could use thin double sided tape between the boards.
  • Bend the pins on the micro slide switch to 90 degrees before inserting
  • Bend the pins on the 4xAAA battery holder flat and cut them short to fit within the large PCB pads; align the mounting holes but attach the holder with double sided foam tape. Note you may wish to file the solder pads and M2 screws to make this fit flush.

Printed parts:

  • Top shell
  • Bottom shell
  • Directional button
  • Round button x 2
  • Spacer x 2

Electronics

  • PCB (see Eagle files)
  • Arduino Nano
  • 1.2" 8x8 LED Matrix with HK16K33 backpack Keyestudio + 4-way straight header pins
  • 6x6x5mm tactile switch x 6
  • Micro slide switch SPDT 8.5x4x3.5 body 2.54mm pin spacing
  • Piezo buzzer passive 9mm diameter
  • 4xAAA battery holder PCB mount + batteries

Hardware

  • Self tapping screw No.4 x 12mm x 4
  • M2 x 8mm machine screw x 2 (optional)
  • Double sided foam tape

title: C-Bot Print Cooling Fan Assembly For 30mm Fans

description.text:
After much searching & trying other already available print cooling fan setups, I couldn't find one that I was happy with for my C-Bot.

This print cooling fan setup uses 2x 30mm fans, with the height being adjustable via the rear mounting plate.

The whole assembly attaches to the rear of the main carriage and has a very low profile (ie, doesn't get in the way).

All parts are oriented as I printed them - you will need to use support, see print notes for more info.

The small notch on the rear mount plate should face the rear surface of the carriage, this is so you can fit a cable tie through to secure your fan power cables :-)

You'll need a few M3 bolts of differing lengths (exact details to be added) along with suitable M3 nuts.

You may feel that when you have printed this, some of the parts feel a bit light & not that strong...this is one of those occasions where the whole assembly becomes a lot stronger when all the parts are joined together. I would suggest that you assemble all the parts together first (including fans & ducts), before attaching the mount plate to the carriage as it is a lot easier this way round.

I have used this reliably now for a reasonable amount of print time (20+ print hours) without issue and have found the cooling to be excellent. It should still be regarded as work in progress, but I feel it is completely usable.

title: HOTAS Throttle Joystick
license: Creative Commons - Attribution - Non-Commercial - Share Alike

description.text:
For a while I've been playing flight simulation games using a normal flight stick and my keyboard/mouse.
But I got sick of this and started researching the cost of a HOTAS throttle joystick and found that these are absurdly priced.
After that I started with a simple breadboard, an Arduino Micro, a PS2 thumb joystick and some buttons.
Using the Adafruit Joystick library I was able to very easily make a prototype joystick with which I could control my vehicles in games.
But I've got a 3D printer, so using it on a breadboard is no fun. Time to design a case for it!

Included are all files needed to make the general joystick, including the specific adapter I used for my potentiometers.
The total amount of inputs on this device are 14 buttons, 2 axis for the thumbstick and 1 axis for the throttle itself.

Printer Brand:

RepRap

Printer:

GEEETech i3 Pro B

Rafts:

No

Supports:

Yes

Resolution:

0.2mm layer height

Infill:

15-25%

Notes:

Print the case/case-top/case-top-deco with the bottom on the bed, this to provide a smooth area.
For the handle, print it on the closed side and give the holes some support to prevent warping so the buttons will fit in.
The handle-endcap is a bit tricky, print it with the outer part facing up and with quite heavy support to ensure that the outer shell will be smooth.

After printing the case and case-top, do a test fit to see if the USB cable hole is the right size. If not, file it down so that it is.

As for the handle, take your time and do a test fit without hardware installed. If it's too tight you will have a hard time getting it apart or have the parts breaking all together.

I took a shape that fit in my hand comfortably and used the size of that to shape the handle, from there I printed test parts and added holes to the handle to keep testing alignment.
After about 4 versions I have the one I am uploading now, I hope that it will fit most hand sizes.

Design

The device runs on a Arduino Pro Micro using the Game Controller library found here;
https://github.com/MHeironimus/ArduinoJoystickLibrary

I have included my Arduino code with the files of this Thing, I also included a schematic of the 4 connection types in the controller.
I will not write a complete tutorial unfortunately, but with a bit of patience you should be able to work out how the other connections need to go.
I will write out what each wire type is;
Red = Vcc / 5V / 3,3V
Blue = Gnd / 0V
Green = Signal wire for throttle
Orange = Signal wire for the button string, this works using a resistor ladder
Purple = Signal wire for the single button
Yellow = Signal wire for the button inside the PS2 thumbstick
White/Cyan = Signal wires for the X and Y axis of the thumbstick

For the exact connections, just check the code and wire accordingly...or don't, I'm not your mother. You can of course just change the pins in the code, to take note that except for the single buttons, the signal wires from all other components need a analog pin on the Arduino to work

Hinges are made with a "Tight" Tolerance, to provide a slight tension after inserting the M3 Screws. This allows the screen to hold open or shut, without springs or latches. Just keep the screws Snug.

Hinge is made to bond the 2 Halves together, providing a greater support for larger screens. (10 - 13.1")

Printing under 40% will make weak Mounting posts that break off with ease and cannot be tapped for a screw to be inserted. At that infill, they simply twist right off the model.

Finishing and Bonding... Final Assembly...

Trim the Brim Neatly from all parts. Try to be as Even as possible. The seam will show a lot otherwise.

Glue the 2 halves together by standing them up on a table, one atop the other. This creates just enough pressure to bond them with Superglue. Be sure to glue all contacting surfaces between the two halves. A good bond makes it feel like one piece afterwards.

(Superglue works well, but leaves a white film on every joining point. Gorilla glue works very well and makes a much stronger union of the parts. But more clamping is required, as the glue expands a lot, even in small amounts.)

Gently work the hinges down onto the tabs BEFORE allowing the model to Fully dry. This will ensure the hinges are able to fit, and that the glue (Like Gorilla Glue), cannot push the hinges apart while drying/reacting.

Lay down on Plastic Wrap to Completely Dry. As it peels away easily or can be trimmed.

Work out all the Screw/Hinge holes with a Drill bit, making sure that it gives the screws you are using enough clearance not to break off the posts.

Add the Speakers to the Tabs as Shown. I Used Gorilla Glue here, and for all of version 2.0, to bond the halves. Just be sure to clamp it and use minimal glue. Gorilla glue expands as it dries.

Shorten the speaker and USB cables coming from them to fit into the case, making sure they reach the USB sound card or SoC Sound Jack, and the Battery USB Port.

Left = 1AMP 5v (Speakers)
Middle = 2.1AMP 5v (USB Hub) Requires a 5v 2MM to USB Cable
Right = 2.4AMP 5v (Odroid or SoC of choice)

Screw in the SoC of Choice, Solder up a USB power Cable for the SoC to the Battery and your Monitor, Power it all up, and Connect your Rii Keyboard!

title: Dual Print Y for SmartrapCore V.2

description.text:
After having spent a huge amount of time and many prototypes on a Twin Head support for the SmartrapCore (http://www.thingiverse.com/thing:995640), which is one of the most complex and difficult designs I've ever made, I realized that some people were successfully experimenting with a much simpler design : a Y-shaped piece that would lead the filament from two sources to a unique hot end, with a filament switching process that would only need a longer retract.

Here are the already functionnal designs :

  • Prometheus : https://www.kickstarter.com/projects/811909269/the-prometheus-system-intuitive-multi-filament-3d?token=7d9207f0
  • 3Dator Y-piece : http://www.thingiverse.com/thing:1680034
  • Prusa i3 MK2 dual/quad extrusion : http://prusaprinters.org/original-prusa-i3-mk2-multi-material-upgrade-release/

So… Of course, it was kind of depressing to think that my long and hard work on the TwinHead design might become useless in the end but, hey, that's life, and I learned a lot in the process, anyway. If there's a better (and most of all much simpler) idea, I guess it's worth a try. :)

Here's my own attempt at using this idea : a quite simple Y piece, specifically designed to fit the SmartrapCore.

Which means you just need a second extruder (with the exact same specs as the first one), a second bowden, and of course a second filament spool.

I didn't make any print with this yet, it's really a work in progress. Of course, it will need a lot of tweaking to get the perfect Start code and head switch code to have this make a dual print as needed, but it's a start. So far, setting this part on the hot end and installing pneufits works perfectly. If you feel like trying to actually experimenting dual extrusion with it, be my guest. :)

Update (dec.14th 2016) : this a 2nd version. Didn't fully test it yet, but the filament goes much more easily to the hot end with this new one, because the filament path has a smoother angle, so I guess it has much better chances to be a good candidate. Also, the pneufit threads on top are the same size as the one that goes into the cooling metalic radiator part on the top of the hot end, so you won't have to change the pneufit to try this device, and you'll only have to install another one on the second extruder's bowden.

This is a Spool Carrier designed specifically to fit inside the airtight bag used to store E3D's SpoolWorks Scaffold Soluble Support. It will work with all SpoolWorks 200mm Spools (500g/750g) . Supports both 2.85mm & 1.75mm filament.

Read the Fulll, detailed, blog post about E3D's Scaffold at | Scaffold Blog Post.

Print with your favourite thermoplastic | http://e3d-online.com/All-Filament

Consider the Heavy-Duty Air-Tight Filament Spool Case as an alternative.

2 x 608ZZ Bearings.
1 x 1.75mm or 2.85mm Thread Bowden Coupling.
1 x Matched Length of PTFE.
6 x M3 10mm Socket Cap Screws.
6 x M3 Hex nuts.
1 x M8 50mm Socket Cap Screw.
1 x M8 Hex Half Nut.

Using the Carrier

Slide the spool onto the carrier and load it into the bag making sure the hole for the bowden coupling is facing towards the bag's opening.

Guestimate an approximate place in the bag where it aligns with the hole for the bowden coupling and make a small cut in the bag.

Fit the optional O-Ring over the threaded section of the bowden coupling. Screw the coupling into the hole ensuring a good seal.

Attach your PTFE to the coupling, feed in some Scaffold and then seal up the bag. Remember to leave the included packet of silica gel in the bag.

You're all set!

description.text:
This is a remix of http://www.thingiverse.com/thing:1798009
I tried to make it more simply to print and mount.
What changes:

  • Don't need to stop midprint. All parts printed normaly.
  • Srcrew holes for M3. Screw directly to plastic. Don't need inserts.
  • Changed printed ball bearing for common 16mm marble ball.
  • Magnet ring in the previous design can be now a simple printed ring, a magnet ring or a 625ZZ bearing.
  • 'Cam' changed to 2 momentary 'clik' buttons.
    -Detailed mounting instructions.

IMPORTANT NOTE: For a good finish, you may need to sand and glue some parts during mounting. I don't mention this in the instructions but you must remember always when you mount a part.
